{
  "local_port": 46704,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How can you determine the molecular mass of ammonium?",
  "response": "To determine the molecular mass of **ammonium (NH\u2084\u207a)**, you can follow these steps:\n\n### 1. **Identify the Constituent Atoms**\n\nAmmonium consists of:\n- **Nitrogen (N)**\n- **Hydrogen (H)**\n\n### 2. **Find the Atomic Mass of Each Element**\n\nUsing the periodic table, locate the atomic masses:\n- **Nitrogen (N):** ~14.01\u202fg/mol\n- **Hydrogen (H):** ~1.008\u202fg/mol\n\n### 3. **Calculate the Total Mass for Each Element**\n\nAmmonium has:\n- **1 Nitrogen atom:**  \n  \\( 1 \\times 14.01 \\, \\text{g/mol} = 14.01 \\, \\text{g/mol} \\)\n\n- **4 Hydrogen atoms:**  \n  \\( 4 \\times 1.008 \\, \\text{g/mol} = 4.032 \\, \\text{g/mol} \\)\n\n### 4. **Sum the Masses to Get the Molecular Mass**\n\nAdd the masses of all constituent atoms:\n\\[\n\\text{Molecular mass of NH}_4^+ = 14.01 \\, \\text{g/mol} + 4.032 \\, \\text{g/mol} = 18.042 \\, \\text{g/mol}\n\\]\n\n### **Final Molecular Mass**\n\nThe molecular mass of ammonium ion (NH\u2084\u207a) is **approximately 18.04\u202fg/mol**.\n\n### **Additional Notes**\n\n- **Charge Consideration:** While ammonium carries a positive charge (NH\u2084\u207a), the molecular mass calculation considers only the masses of the atoms, not the charge.\n  \n- **Rounding:** Depending on the level of precision required, you might round the final molecular mass. For most purposes, **18.04\u202fg/mol** is sufficiently accurate.\n\n### **Example Calculation Summary**\n\n| Element | Number of Atoms | Atomic Mass (g/mol) | Total Mass (g/mol) |\n|---------|-----------------|---------------------|--------------------|\n| Nitrogen (N) | 1               | 14.01               | 14.01              |\n| Hydrogen (H) | 4               | 1.008               | 4.032              |\n| **Total**    | -               | -                   | **18.042**         |\n\nThus, **NH\u2084\u207a** has a molecular mass of **18.04\u202fg/mol**.",
